analytic.title: SUBGROUPS AND OUTCOMES IN EATING DISORDERS TREATMENT

abstract.p: Objective: Psychological treatment effects and response rates have largely plateaued over the past few decades. A potential answer to this problem is personalized treatment approaches, which match treatment to a client's specific presenting concerns, which should increase its precision and efficacy. Examining predictors and moderators of treatment outcome (who is likely to benefit from treatment, and which treatment) is one way to guide such personalized decision making. The current study aimed to investigate the relationship between network-derived subgroups, treatment condition, and treatment response using data from two clinical trials on eating disorders (N = 80). This study is also a proof-of-concept for the clinical utility of network-based subgroups. Method: Subgroups were identified using Subgrouping Group Iterative Multiple Model Estimation (S-GIMME) and ANOVAs were used to compare changes in symptom severity and clinical impairment among subgroups. Results: We found three subgroups (n = 71; mean age = 34.4 [SD = 11.8], 87.3% cisgender women, 85.9% white, non-Hispanic), which were differentiated by how shame and guilt were related in the network. The subgroup with a contemporaneous pathway from guilt to shame showed the least improvement in clinical impairment from pre-to posttreatment (F(2, 64) = 5.92, p = .004). Conclusions: Overall, our findings suggest that network-based subgroups may have utility as prognostic indicators, at least in the context of eating disorders, though replication of present findings is warranted. Limitations included potentially unstable subgroups and use of mostly cisgender women and white samples.

div.head: Examining the Relationship Between Network-Based Subgroups and Treatment Outcomes Among Individuals with Eating Disorders
div.p: Over the past several decades, there has been an increase in the number of individuals who seek and receive treatment for mental health concerns (Kessler et al., 2005;Lipson et al., 2022), yet mental health treatment effects have largely remained stagnant (Cuijpers et al., 2024).

Generally, treatment response hovers around 50% for mental health conditions, including eating disorders (Atwood & Friedman, 2020), depression (Cuijpers et al., 2021), and anxiety disorders (Loerinc et al., 2015). Although these findings lend support to the fact that we have effective treatments for some people, they also underscore a need for interventions that are effective for more than half of people.

One potential explanation for why existing evidence-based treatments fail to meet the needs of all people is that commonly disseminated manualized treatments were developed for the aggregate, and thus may not address the person-specific processes relevant to the individual in the therapy room (Fisher, 2015;Fisher & Boswell, 2016;Levinson, Cusack, et al., 2022;Spring, 2007). In an effort to design more effective psychotherapeutic interventions, scholars have investigated personalized approaches to psychotherapy, in which interventions are matched to an individual's symptoms and context rather than assigned diagnoses (Cohen & DeRubeis, 2018;Cuijpers et al., 2016;Fisher, 2015;Hofmann & Hayes, 2019). Of the methods used to personalize psychotherapy, a network-informed approach has been investigated for treating mental health concerns, including anxiety, mood, and eating disorders (Burger et al., 2024;Fisher et al., 2017Fisher et al., , 2019Klintwall et al., 2023;Levinson et al., 2023). Although participants in these trials show promising outcomes (i.e., symptom reduction for their respective concerns), we lack methods to determine who will respond to such approaches and to what degree. For example, certain people may respond better to manualized treatment, obviating the need to target specific problems in context, whereas others may benefit more from personalized treatment.

div.head: Prognostic Utility of Psychological Networks
div.p: Scholars have used metrics derived from psychological networks to select personalized treatment targets and interventions as well as predict treatment response. These metrics include indices of global network structure, such as connectivity (i.e., the cumulative strength of correlations between symptoms), and of node-level importance, such as strength centrality (i.e., the absolute value of edges extending from a single node; Robinaugh et al., 2020). Overall, the literature is mixed on how network connectivity relates to treatment response. Some studies found that greater network connectivity at baseline predicts poor treatment response (van Borkulo et al., 2015); others showed that decreased network connectivity at baseline and increased connectivity across treatment is associated with improved treatment response (McElroy et al., 2019). Still, other work found that baseline network connectivity was not related to treatment outcomes (Hilbert et al., 2020;Schweren et al., 2018). In terms of node-level metrics, a symptom's strength centrality have been found to change over the course of treatment and be temporally associated with symptom severity across sessions (Bringmann et al., 2015;Park et al., 2021). Further, node strength centrality from idiographic, time-series networks may account for significant variability in symptom change scores at 6-month follow-up (Cusack, Ralph-Nearman, et al., 2024). Together, these results suggest that node-level metrics derived from psychological networks may offer prognostic value for short-(e.g., session-to-session) and long-term clinical outcomes, though their direction of association appears to be inconsistent.

More research on networks and treatment outcomes is needed to clarify factors contributing to ostensibly inconsistent findings and identify replicable patterns that may proffer helpful prognostic information in different contexts.

div.head: Group Iterative Multiple Model Estimation
div.p: A statistical approach that holds potential for investigating the prognosis in networkinformed personalized treatment is group iterative multiple model estimation (GIMME). GIMME uses time-series data to leverage group-level commonalities in symptom associations while accounting for person-level idiosyncrasies (Gates & Molenaar, 2012). In psychological networks, a GIMME-identified subgroup represents a cluster of individuals with similar network structures. This type of approach that borrows from both schools of thought (i.e., nomothetic and idiographic) may be particularly useful in examining as prognostic tool for personalized treatment outcomes because it allows researchers to examine individuals and subgroups (e.g., how does one person or a subgroup respond vs. what a clinician might expect on average; Wright & Woods, 2020). Moreover, focusing on subgroup-level similarities may facilitate development of more parsimonious personalized treatment informed by reliable recurring patterns across individuals, rather than creating a unique treatment plan for every single client.

div.head: Eating Disorders as a Clinical Example
div.p: Eating disorders are mental disorders characterized by extreme behaviors associated with food intake (e.g., caloric restriction, compensatory behaviors, binge eating) and psychological disturbance regarding shape and/or weight (e.g., over-evaluation of shape/weight, perceiving one's emaciated body as "fat," intense fear of weight gain). Eating disorders are a model system to examine the prognostic value of networks using GIMME because individuals with eating disorders show marked heterogeneity in symptom presentations (Levinson, Hunt, et al., 2022). A method that accounts for this heterogeneity while classifying meaningful subgroups may yield clinically pertinent information, such as treatment outcomes (e.g., symptom severity, global functioning), which can then be used to guide treatment planning.

div.head: Current Study
div.p: The current study examined (1) whether subgroups identified using GIMME were related to clinical outcomes (changes in eating disorder symptoms and clinical impairment) in psychotherapy for eating disorders and (2) if this relationship was moderated by treatment condition. The broader objective was a proof of concept to see if GIMME-derived networks could be meaningfully associated with clinical outcomes in a particular context (eating disorders, in this case). We used data from two clinical trials on eating disorders, wherein participants received one of three treatment conditions: (1) up to 10 sessions of Brief Transdiagnostic Network-Informed Personalized Treatment for Eating Disorders (PT-10; Levinson et al., 2023),

(2) up to 20 sessions of Transdiagnostic Network-Informed Personalized Treatment for Eating Disorders (PT-20; Butler et al., 2023), and (3) up to 20 sessions of Enhanced Cognitive Behavioral Therapy for Eating Disorders (CBT-20; Butler et al., 2023). We hypothesized that subgroup membership would be significantly related to treatment outcomes, though we did not predict a specific direction of association as this study was largely exploratory and subgroups were not defined a priori.

div.head: Data Transparency and Openness
div.p: This study was preregistered at https://osf.io/qk9h7. Analysis code and supplementary materials are available at https://osf.io/8kvdm/. Data are available via reasonable request of the last author. We report how we determined our sample size, all data exclusions, all manipulations, and all measures in the current study.

div.head: Diagnostic Interviews
div.p: Study personnel determined eating disorder diagnoses by administering the eating disorder modules from the Structured Clinical Interview for DSM-5 (First et al., 2015), which has been shown to have good interrater reliability, test-retest reliability, and convergent validity (Osório et al., 2019). Exclusion criteria and co-occurring disorders were assessed using the Mini International Neuropsychiatric Interview (Sheehan et al., 1997(Sheehan et al., , 1998. Participants were eligible for the studies if they were between the ages of 18 and 65 (inclusive) and met diagnostic criteria for an eating disorder (i.e., anorexia nervosa, bulimia nervosa, binge eating disorder, and other specified feeding or eating disorder) that was active or in partial remission. Partial remission was defined as meeting criteria for an eating disorder in past year and still having clinically significant cognitions or behaviors. Exclusion criteria included the presence of any of the following: current manic episode, current psychosis, imminent suicidal intent, currently receiving any other psychotherapeutic treatment specifically focused on their eating disorder, or medical instability. Medical instability was defined as a combination of several physical symptoms, including seeing blurred vision or dark spots within the past 24 hours, experiencing dizziness especially when going from sitting to standing, shortness of breath, current chest pain, purging more than three times in the past 24 hours, consuming fewer than 500 kcal in the past 48 hours, and BMI < 17.

div.head: Treatment Outcomes
div.p: Eating Disorder Symptom Severity. The Eating Disorder Examination Questionnaire 6.0 (EDE-Q; Fairburn & Beglin, 2008) is a 28-item self-report instrument that asks participants to rate eating disorder symptoms over the past 28 days on a 0 (no days, not at all) to 6 (every day, markedly) scale. The global score from the EDE-Q was used to measure eating disorder symptom severity. The EDE-Q global score is calculated by computing the average of four subscales: Restraint, Eating Concern, Shape Concern, and Weight Concern. Higher scores reflect greater symptom severity. The EDE-Q has good reliability and validity in clinical samples (Berg et al., 2012;Luce & Crowther, 1999). The internal consistency of the EDE-Q was good ( = 0.84) in the current sample 1 .

Clinical Impairment. The Clinical Impairment Assessment (CIA; Bohn et al., 2008) is a 16-item questionnaire that assesses impairment due to one's eating disorder across life domains (e.g., personal impairment, social impairment, cognitive impairment). Items are rated on a 0 (not at all) to 3 (a lot) scale. A global score of impairment is obtained by summing items, with higher scores indicating greater impairment resulting from one's eating disorder. The CIA demonstrates good internal consistency and convergent and discriminant validity (Raykos et al., 2019).
Internal consistency for the current study was excellent ( = 0.90) in the current sample 1 .

div.head: Procedure
div.p: Data came from two clinical trials examining personalized treatment for eating disorders.

Both studies were approved by a university institutional review board and participants provided informed consent prior to study participation. The first was a randomized clinical trial which investigated the efficacy of PT-20 and CBT-20 (Butler et al., 2023). Participants were randomly assigned to either PT-20 (n = 14) or CBT-20 (n = 13), where they received up to 20 sessions of individual therapy 1 . Participants completed measures at the following timepoints: pretreatment, immediately upon terminating treatment (henceforth, post-treatment), 6-month follow-up, and 12-month follow-up. Pretreatment and posttreatment assessments were used for the current study, as data collection for other time-points are ongoing. Data for the PT-10 come from an open series trial where participants received 10 individual therapy sessions (Levinson et al., 2023).
Participants completed measures pretreatment, posttreatment, and at 6-month follow-up.
Postdoctoral scholars and clinical psychology graduate students served as study therapists for both studies and received weekly supervision by a licensed clinical psychologist.

For all three treatment conditions, the first two sessions included diagnostic assessment and the third comprised psychoeducation on the participant's treatment condition. In both studies, participants were trained and enrolled in the ecological momentary assessment (EMA) procedure in session 1. Participants were asked to complete brief, EMA surveys five times per day for 15 days, from session 1 to session 3, where they rated their momentary experience with eating disorder and co-occurring symptoms. There were 42 symptom/modules that pertained to eating disorder symptoms (e.g., regular eating module to target restriction), co-occurring symptoms (e.g., exposure therapy for social anxiety), and transdiagnostic symptoms (e.g., selfcompassion for self-criticism). Participants were asked to complete additional EMA surveys if errors presented in the participant networks due to insufficient observations or variability. EMA data were then used to estimate idiographic networks to inform the personalized treatment condition (treatment started on session 4 for both studies).

For participants in the PT-20 condition, session 4 through 18 included symptom-specific modules based on their top three to four most central symptoms identified in their pretreatment network, and the last two sessions focused on relapse prevention and termination. Participants in the CBT-E condition worked through the stages of CBT-E from session 4 through 17 (Fairburn, 2008). Stage 1 involves developing a collaborative case conceptualization of one's eating disorder, psychoeducation on eating disorder behaviors and medical consequences, and addressing problematic eating behaviors through regular eating and reducing compensatory behaviors (e.g., purging). Stage 2 is a transitional stage where the patient and clinician reflect on progress made in Stage 1 and plan for Stage 3. Stage 3 targets eating disorder maintenance factors with auxiliary modules, such as those focused on overevaluation of weight and shape, dietary restraint, event-or mood-related changes to eating, low self-esteem, and perfectionism.
Participants and therapists selected two to three modules for Stage 3. The treatment concluded with two to three sessions discussing relapse prevention and preparing for treatment termination.
For the PT-10 condition, sessions 4 through 9 included modules that addressed participants top two most central symptoms, and session 10 focused on relapse prevention and termination.

div.head: Data Analytic Plan
div.p: Analyses were done in RStudio using R version 4.3.3 (Posit Team, 2024; R Core Team, 2024). Data wrangling was done using the tidyverse, clock, and rio packages (Chan et al., 2018;Vaughan, 2024;Wickham, 2017).

div.head: Missing Outcome Data
div.p: Missing data for the EDE-Q and CIA variables at pre-and posttreatment were imputed for participants who had started each questionnaire. For the RCT dataset, the missing data rate was 232/9,405 (2.47%). For the open trial dataset, the total proportion of missing data was 26.82% (1838/6853). The rate is high because the CIA was only introduced later in the open series trial. The monotone method in the mice R package was used to impute missing values (van Buuren & Groothuis-Oudshoorn, 2011).

div.head: Data Preprocessing
div.p: To ensure sufficient power to detect reliable subgroups, we first identified a subset of variables to include as nodes in the estimated networks, as recovery of true paths have been found to improve with more timepoints and fewer variables (Lane et al., 2019). For example, for a network containing 10 variables with freely estimated autoregressive pathways and 60 timepoints, average path recovery was 68.2%, whereas the same recovery rate for five variables was 88.6% (Lane et al., 2019). As the number of timepoints is fixed in our secondary analyses, we sought to reduce network variables. To select variables for present networks, we referred to results from a prior study using data that overlap with current analyses (Cusack, Vanzhula, et al., 2024). In the study, the authors examined strength centrality indices of various variables depending on what other variables were included in the same network. Specifically, they examined the stability of strength centrality of network variables across 1,000 networks with unique eight-node combinations. To maximize clinical relevance of our networks with the fewest number of nodes, we chose to include the top eight most consistent variables with respect to strength centrality: shame ("I feel ashamed"), guilt ("I feel guilty"), overvaluation of weight and shape ("My weight and/or shape is influencing how I think"), always worrying ("I am worrying about something and/or feel overwhelmed"), fear of losing control ("I am afraid of losing control"), self-criticism ("I'm disapproving and judgmental about my own flaws"), overwhelming emotions ("I am experiencing my emotions as overwhelming and"), and feeling ineffective ("I feel ineffective as a person"). Eight was selected based on recommendations from a simulation study, to minimize issues of low sensitivity (Type II error; Mansueto et al., 2023), while balancing the theoretical need to adequately represent complex clinical presentations (Levinson, Hunt, et al., 2022).

In the following step, we reviewed and processed the data to ensure they were suitable for GIMME analyses. First, to address the assumption of weak stationarity of GIMME (Beltz & Gates, 2017), detrending of variables for which there was a significant linear trend was conducted. For these variables, data were regressed on cumulative time in ordinary least squares regression models using the lm function in the stats package (R Core . Residuals from these models were used in place of original values. Second, a row of NAs was added at the end of each day to prevent a datapoint from the previous evening predicting a datapoint the following morning when estimating lagged pathways. Following this step, consecutive rows of NA were removed to streamline analyses, leaving only one row of NA values between observations. Because GIMME examines how variables covary, participants/timepoint combinations (e.g., participant 1 at pre-vs. posttreatment) that had variables with zero variation (i.e., only one unique value during the period of data collection) were removed from analyses (n = 30 across 24 participants). Next, participant/timepoint combinations that had fewer than 30 data points in any of the network variables were removed, per the minimum data requirement for running GIMME (n = 63 across 45 participants), leaving 146 participants with 160 participant/timepoint combinations (some participants provided pre-and posttreatment data).

To test our research questions about treatment effects, we also removed participants who completed fewer than five treatment sessions (n = 54), as they were deemed to have received an inadequate dose of treatment (one module of treatment would have been delivered with six sessions). For the purpose of predicting outcomes, we excluded participants who were missing both EDE-Q and CIA change scores (i.e., no outcome data; n = 10). The number of participants left was 82 (with 94 participant/timepoint combinations; 81 at pretreatment and 13 at posttreatment).

div.head: Model Estimation and Interpretation
div.p: Subgrouping Group Iterative Multiple Model Estimation (S-GIMME) was used to identify subgroups based on network characteristics using the gimmeSEM function in the gimme R package (Gates et al., 2017;Lane et al., 2019Lane et al., , 2021. S-GIMME extends the GIMME procedure, which has been found to reliably identify group-and individual-level pathways in idiographic networks, by additionally enabling the identification of subgroup-level pathways (Gates et al., 2017). GIMME relies on unified structural equation modeling (uSEM) to model contemporaneous and lagged (including autoregressive) relations among variables of interest (Gates et al., 2010;Kim et al., 2007). The ability to simultaneously model contemporaneous and lagged effects has several advantages. S-GIMME begins with the estimation of group-level pathways (shared by at least 75% of the sample) to minimize influence of noise in the data and to improve recovery of individuallevel pathways (Gates & Molenaar, 2012). For current analyses, the search procedure started with a null model for each participant with autoregressive elements freely estimated. In the group-level search, the S-GIMME algorithm identifies pathways that are found to significantly improve individual model fit for the majority of the sample (set as 75%; Gates & Molenaar, 2012), using modification indices, which are Lagrange multiplier tests (Engle, 1984). This group-level search continues until no pathways meet the 75% threshold. To minimize spurious pathways, pathways that are no longer significantly improve model fit for at least 75% of participants are pruned.

In the next step, subgroups within the dataset are identified based on shared characteristics of temporal processes across individuals (Lane et al., 2019). Specifically, similarity is determined by correspondence between estimated pathways from the first step and the expected parameter change associated with each pathway that could be added to the model (analogous to the modification indices in the group-level search, but accounts for pathway directionality). Then, the Walktrap community detection procedure is used to cluster individual models based on these characteristics (Pons & Latapy, 2006). Once subgroups have been identified, a subgroup-level search procedure, parallel to the group-level search conducted in the first step, is used to identify pathways shared among at least 51% of subgroup members, starting with the model with group-level pathways (rather than a null model).
In the final step, individual-level pathways for each participant are identified, starting from the model with group-and subgroup-level pathways estimated from the previous two steps.

In the individual-level search, pathways that significantly improve individual model fit are added iteratively until an "excellent" model fit is obtained. "Excellent" is operationalized as meeting cutoff criteria on two of four commonly used model fit indices: RMSEA ≤ .05, SRMR ≤ .05, NNFI ≥ .95, or CFI ≥ .95 (Bentler, 1990;Hu & Bentler, 1999). Full information maximum likelihood, which handles missing data, was used for model estimation. Given our research questions, subgroup membership was the primary variable of interest, rather than pathways within the networks. We had originally planned to examine networks estimated at pre-and posttreatment, however, due to insufficient EMA data at posttreatment (n = 13; Lane et al., 2019), our analyses only pertain to pretreatment networks and subgroups (N = 81).

To evaluate the robustness of subgroups, we used the perturbR function from the perturbR package (Gates et al., 2019), which incrementally introduces noise to network edges and tests how much the original cluster solution changes in response to these perturbations. Two metrics are used to evaluate similarity between the original and perturbed cluster solutions: the adjusted Rand Index (ARI) and Variation of Information (VI). For the ARI, higher values reflect greater similarity between subgroup assignments, whereas for the VI, lower values reflect greater similarity. A robust solution would be indicated by relatively stable results (i.e., subgroups assignments) despite minor perturbations. For example, the cluster solution should have < 20% of the nodes being assigned to different clusters given < 20% of its edges perturbed (Gates et al., 2019).

div.head: Analysis of Variance (ANOVA)
div.p: Once subgroup membership was determined, we used a two-way ANOVA 2 to evaluate the relationship between pretreatment subgroup membership and clinically relevant outcomes (change in EDE-Q and CIA scores from pre-to posttreatment). ANOVAs were conducted with the aov function in the stats R package (R Core . We calculated change scores (score at posttreatment -score at pretreatment) for eating disorder symptom severity and clinical impairment and used these as dependent variables in separate models. For each model, subgroup membership, treatment condition (levels: PT-10, PT-20, CBT-20), and their interaction term (i.e., subgroup membership×treatment condition) were entered as predictors. To avoid unreliable model estimates due to underpopulated cells, only subgroups with at least 10 members were included. If a predictor was found to be significant overall, Tukey's HSD was used post hoc to identify significant pairwise differences between levels with the TukeyHSD function in the stats package (R Core .

div.head: Network-Based Subgroups
div.p: During the individual-level search procedure, S-GIMME identified issues with one participant, who was excluded from S-GIMME analyses due to having a singular information matrix. Thus, a total of 80 participants at pretreatment were included in subgrouping analyses. Individual-level model fit indices are provided on the study OSF page <https://osf.io/kxwsu>. The S-GIMME procedure identified three subgroups with more than one member, with 19 members in subgroup 1, 36 in subgroup 2, and 16 members in subgroup 3. The remaining participants (n = 9) had sufficiently different networks that they were assigned to their own subgroup of one. Group-level paths showed autoregressive relationships for all variables, indicating that each variable predicted higher scores of itself at the next measured timepoint. The main subgroup-level difference was the path between shame and guilt. In subgroup 1 (Guilt → Shame), guilt predicted shame contemporaneously; in subgroup 3 (Shame → Guilt), shame predicted guilt contemporaneously; whereas there was no subgroup-level relationship between shame and guilt in subgroup 2 (Guilt <> Shame; see Figure 1). Means for EDE-Q and CIA change scores are presented in Table 2.

Results from the incremental perturbation of network edges suggested that subgroups were relatively unstable (i.e., solution changes in response to added noise in data), as the ARI decreased and VI increased precipitously even with minor perturbations (< 20% rewired edges).

For instance, the ARI crossed the 0.8 threshold before 20% of edges were perturbed (Gates et al., 2019). Graphs showing changes in the ARI and VI with increasing proportion of rewired edges are provided in Figure 2.

div.head: Participants
div.p: Only participants who belonged to a subgroup with at least 10 members were included in ANOVA models. The final sample used to examine the relationship between subgroups and clinical outcomes comprised 71 participants (nPT-10 = 44, nRCT = 27). Participants had a mean age of 34.4 years (SD = 11.8,. Most participants were cisgender women (n = 62, 87.3%) and white (n = 61, 85.9%). The most common diagnosis was other specified-feeding and eating disorder (n = 27, 38.0%), followed by anorexia nervosa (n = 17, 23.9%), bulimia nervosa (n = 17, 23.9%), and binge eating disorder (n = 10, 14.1%). Table 1 presents full demographic data by sample. Participants in the RCT completed a mean of 18.2 out of 20 sessions (SD = 4.1) and those in the open series completed a mean of 9.6 (SD = 1.3) out of 10 sessions.

div.head: Predictors of Outcome Change Scores
div.p: No significant predictors were identified for change in EDE-Q from pre-to posttreatment (ps > .05), indicating that subgroup membership was not associated with change in eating disorder severity, partialing out the effects of treatment condition. For the CIA, subgroup membership (F(2, 64) = 5.92, p = .004) and treatment condition (F(2, 64) = 3.85, p = .026) independently significantly predicted change from pre-to posttreatment, though their interaction term was not significant (F(2, 64) = 1.40, p = .254). This finding means that subgroup membership and treatment condition were associated with changes in clinical impairment over the course of treatment, but these effects did not depend on each other.

Post-hoc pairwise comparisons indicated that relative to the Guilt → Shame subgroup, participants in the Guilt <> Shame subgroup (difference = -7.53, 95% CI [-14.16, -0.90], p = .022) and Shame → Guilt subgroup (difference = -10.73, 95% CI [-18.66, -2.80], p = .005) showed greater decreases in clinical impairment. There was no significant difference between the Guilt <> Shame and Shame → Guilt subgroups (difference = -3.20, 95% CI [-10.22, 3.82], p = .521). Comparisons between treatment conditions did not indicate any differences (ps > .10), despite the significant omnibus test. Figure 3 presents line graphs showing the change in CIA scores over time.

div.head: Discussion
div.p: In the current study, we used data from two clinical trials testing personalized treatment for eating disorders (Butler et al., 2023;Levinson et al., 2023) to examine whether subgroups identified based on network similarities had prognostic utility (i.e., were related to treatment outcomes). S-GIMME identified three subgroups (ns ranged from 16 to 36), with the main difference between subgroups being the relationship between shame and guilt. Specifically, in the first subgroup, guilt predicted shame at the same timepoint. In the second subgroup, there was no subgroup-level relationship between shame and guilt, whereas in the third subgroup, shame predicted guilt at the same timepoint. Between-group comparisons indicated that neither subgroup membership nor treatment condition was associated with change in eating disorder severity, though subgroup membership significantly predicted change in clinical impairment, partialing out the effect of treatment condition (interaction term was not significant).

The subgroup with the least change in clinical impairment had a subgroup-level contemporaneous pathway from guilt to shame, whereas the subgroup with no subgroup-level pathway between guilt and shame or with a contemporaneous pathway from shame to guilt showed similar decreases in clinical impairment from pre-to posttreatment (see Figure 3). It is possible that how people relate to shame and guilt has clinical relevance with respect to treatment response for eating disorders. Indeed, research suggests that shame and guilt-with more consistent evidence for shame-contribute to the maintenance of eating disorder symptoms (Blythin et al., 2020;Bottera et al., 2020;Burney & Irwin, 2000), and greater decreases in shame early in treatment have been found to predict faster eating disorder symptom improvement (Kelly et al., 2014). Nonetheless, the low robustness of subgroups in our sample warrants further investigation before reliable conclusions can be made.

On a conceptual level, our results tentatively suggest that subgroups identified using S-GIMME may have clinical relevance with respect to their ability to predict treatment response, albeit only for impairment but not eating disorder severity in our sample. These results are preliminary, given our small sample size and potentially unstable subgroup memberships. Still, the ability to identify these groups in larger samples could be used to distinguish who needs treatment personalization versus existing standardized evidence-based treatments. Networkbased subgroups within a clinical sample may respond differently to treatment has meaningful implications for treatment matching and personalization. Given the global scarcity and inequity of mental health services broadly (Lora et al., 2020), and eating disorders treatment specifically (Penwell et al., 2024), ensuring that people who need help are receiving interventions most likely to work for them-such as by matching treatments to pretreatment networks-may increase efficiency of services and streamline resource use.

Yet, identifying reliable predictors of what treatments will work for whom has been a perennial challenge in clinical psychology (Schneider et al., 2015), with researchers moving toward testing composite moderators that seem to have more utility than individual variables (Niles et al., 2017) and identifying clusters based on individual-level treatment trajectories (Gloster et al., 2024). Beyond such methods, a network approach may be an even more nuanced way to identify treatment moderators by focusing on patterns among clinically relevant variables (i.e., how problems/strengths interrelate)-estimated simultaneously-rather than symptom severity at a singular timepoint or changes in a specific outcome over time. After all, people with the same level of eating disorder severity may present differently, so using a global score by itself, without attending to central symptoms or interrelations among symptoms is necessarily limiting. Nonetheless, a challenge with relying on person-level network-based moderators is the need for intensive longitudinal data and large sample sizes, which may not always be feasible in clinical practice and research studies with less resources.

Another possible use of network-based treatment predictors is informing how to improve treatment to better meet patient needs. Based on our study findings, clarifying how to address shame, guilt, and their interrelation may be important for refining treatment approaches for eating disorders, which have historically prioritized diagnosis-specific symptoms like binge eating rather than difficult emotions relevant to multiple psychological conditions like shame (Hay, 2020). Indeed, recent data suggest that compassion-focused approaches, which target shame and self-criticism, may hold some promise for treating people with eating disorder diagnoses (Gale et al., 2014;Vrabel et al., 2024).

In summary, this study provides preliminary evidence that subgroups derived from shared network characteristics may be able to predict changes in clinical impairment over the course of treatment for eating disorders, but with caveats. Primarily, although the current study was theoretically sufficiently powered to detect meaningful subgroups (Lane et al., 2019), results from perturbation of network edges suggested that subgroups were not stable, which is consistent with findings from a similar study (Murray et al., 2024). Because studies using S-GIMME do not always test robustness of their subgroups (e.g., Wright et al., 2019;Yin et al., 2023), we do not know the extent to which unstable subgroups are endemic in such analyses or if they drastically change overall findings. At this point, our main takeaway is that more observations per participant and more participants are needed to properly test whether network-based subgroups have reliable prognostic utility, and in which contexts.

div.head: Limitations
div.p: First, all participants in the Guilt → Shame subgroup were assigned to the PT-10 condition, so there was a confound between subgroup assignment and treatment condition and we were unable to fully test an interaction effect between subgroup membership and treatment condition. Thus, it is unclear if the smaller change in clinical impairment in the Guilt → Shame subgroup was due to the network characteristics of the subgroup or receiving PT-10 (though participants in the other two subgroups showed greater improvement in the PT-10 condition).

Moreover, there might be a significant interaction effect, wherein participants from certain subgroups are more likely to respond to a particular treatment (e.g., the Guilt → Shame subgroup would respond better to CBT-20), but we were not able to detect this with our current sample size. Second, evaluation of subgroup membership stability suggested that the original solution was not robust, so our findings may not replicate in a larger or different sample, and further tests are needed. A study that examined the link between GIMME-derived subgroups from functional magnetic neuroimaging data and clinical outcomes in adults in nicotine dependence similarly found an unstable cluster solution (Murray et al., 2024), so it appears that this issue is not unique to self-report data. Nonetheless, larger data sets with sufficiently populated cells would be more likely to produce a stable cluster solution. Third, we could not examine whether posttreatment networks were associated with outcomes due to insufficient data, and this would have provided additional context for our interpretations. Fourth, information gleaned from our network-based subgroups is limited by the variables we chose to include in the networks. Networks estimated using a different subset of variables might have produced different results, though we attempted to address this problem by selecting nodes that were most consistently central across a range of node combinations (Cusack, Vanzhula, et al., 2024). Finally, most of our sample identified as cisgender women and white, providing little information on how personalized treatments work for people with marginalized identities. This gap is particularly meaningful as men and people of color are typically underrepresented in eating disorder treatment research (Burnette et al., 2022), so data on evidence-based treatments are not fully representative of the range of client experiences to begin with. Moreover, given that contextual and cultural variables are likely to influence eating disorder presentations, including maintenance factors, personalized treatments could be key to adequately addressing these important variables that are not always considered in diagnosis-focused treatments. Thus, testing how people with marginalized identities respond to personalized treatment seems like a critical area of focus for eating disorder research-and personalized treatment research more broadly.

div.head: Conclusion
div.p: The current study was a proof of concept to determine if network-based subgroups had clinical utility with respect to predicting treatment outcomes over time. Our results indicated that pretreatment subgroups differentiated by the nature of the relationship between shame and guilt were associated with varying improvement in clinical impairment. It is possible that how shame and guilt are targeted in eating disorder treatment may influence treatment response, though our findings require replication with larger samples, other clinical populations, and a broader set of clinically meaningful outcomes.

Second, it minimizes spurious effects that might occur due to excluding lagged pathways from the estimated model. Third, including contemporaneous effects avoids the issue of such effects being otherwise incorrectly designated as error correlations or inflated lagged effects.
